Locality: Pescadero Creek Rd.-- Butano Creek riparian area
Observation Details: Continuing bird. Very active - watched for 15 minutes - fed in 8 trees - the red breasted sapsucker in my yard has only used 7 trees in 4 years of watching. Derek got pictures.   Where we found it - along East side of creek about .2 miles north of road - look back towards road and we saw the bird at the last spot you can still see the bridge over the creek.  Separate Red patches at throat, crown and nape - with two lines of white bars along back.  It’s been a while since I have seen a red-naked that is not an intergrade with a red-breasted....

While biking a dull color caught my attention by the creek and I was satisfied to see it was a snipe. Got my camera out to take a photo and when I relooked one my bins I realized there were many more. Most I’ve ever seen in one spot

In red berry tree where rbg grosbeaks seen. Derek got pictures. Then flew to euc above berry tree. Saw 4 or 5 times over 5-8 minutes. Loosely  warbling vireo.  Knew it wasn't a wRbling vireo as its back was yellowish-green with very grey hood with high contrast. Wanted to call it a red-eyed vireo but no contrast on face markings and eye not red. Got derek on bird and somehow he got picks. Picks seen by several (Oscar and Cedric) and called yellow green vireo. Also called out and Calvin had just arrived and his impression was Yellow green.  Absolutely amazing! Thought it was too windy but still went out and this was the reward.
Might have wing-related injury. The bird was vigorously preening the entire time I watched it.

Locality: Napa-Sonoma Marshes WA--Napa River Units - Pond 1
Observation Details: Seen with flock of terns and flocks in perfect late day light. Petite gull with tiny black bill, mostly brown face with some white around the eyes.  Were also fortunate to see it in flight with it's interesting patterned wing upperparts as it flushed with about a dozen terns. We lost it in the rush and it wasn't until about 30 minutes later that John Sterling relocated it by scope view far away to the northwest.

Locality: Napa-Sonoma Marshes WA--Napa River Units - Pond 1

Locality: Coyote Point County Park--harbor and marsh
Observation Details: Immature bird best views - in front of yacht club building - I hope Derek posts the The pictures  of this desert sparrow bathing. I did not realize these guys were so tiny until I saw this bird side by side with a junco and white throated sparrow - maybe 2/3 the size...  Supposed resident desert bird but I think desert birds disperse as they are alwAys dealing with droughts and that explains what this bird is in San Mateo - a young bird off course as pRt of a desert related natural dispersal.

Viewed with 3 other birders. Opportunity to identify improved when the entire shorebird flock flushed due to a Peregrine Falcon attack. Easiest to identify within the flock by searching for the one without barring, etc. on the back.

This godwit stuck out noticeably from the other godwits perched on the boardwalk.  It's head was tucked in most of the time but finally gave some good looks. Unfortunately, when all of the shorebirds flushed from the boardwalk as the tide receded, no one was able to pick up this bird in flight to get more field marks.  The godwits dispersed to various areas that were not easily visible from the boardwalk area.
